<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-699-812  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 699 812.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  August 1989 v29 n8 p23(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An apple a day and at night: a distance tutoring program forat-risk students.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ross, Steven M.; Smith, Lana; Morrison, Gary; Erickson, Ann.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Memphis Apple Classroom of Tomorrow (ACOT) project, acooperative effort begun in 1986 by Apple Computer and schools inMemphis, TN is described.andP;  ACOT focuses on &quot;distance tutoring&quot; viacomputer for at-risk minority students.andP;  Participating studentseach receive one computer to use at school and another to use athome, then communicate with personal tutors over an electronicBulletin Board System (BBS).andP;  Students are first trained tooperate their computer equipment and BBS, then receive assignmentsdesigned to enhance their reading and writing skills.andP;  ACOTdemonstrates the potential of distance tutoring to help at-riskchildren learn and gain self-confidence.andP;  Distance tutoring ismost effective with at-risk children when it is personalized andhumanized, when its BBS operation facilitates tutor-studentinteractions, when assignments match regular classroom learningactivities, and when parents are involved.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (education policy).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     EducationComputer-Assisted InstructionCase StudyHuman FactorsOff-Site.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>